The Time Has Come for More Restrictions on Military Transfers of Equipment to Civilian Police

Rule Of Law Post, 2020

Center for Ethics and the Rule of Law at the University of Pennsylvania

4 Pages Posted: 16 Jul 2020
See all articles by Kevin H. Govern
Kevin H. Govern

Ave Maria University - Ave Maria School of Law

Date Written: June 23, 2020
Abstract

The presence of military equipment and military munitions in the hands of civilian law enforcement can cause an escalation of violence and reinforcing mistrust between the people and the police. There are enough concerns about the transfer of military equipment to civilian law enforcement that the current federal transfer program should be temporarily halted. Such a hiatus would enable lawmakers to ensure that future transfers, should they resume, are fully consistent with the police reform measures outlined by the president in Executive Order 13929.

Keywords: Defense Support To Civil Authorities, DSCA, 1033 Program, Executive Orders, Militarization of Police, Military Equipment, Surplus, Congressional Oversight, Insurrection Act, Illegal Behavior and the Enforcement of Law

JEL Classification: K10, K14, K42

